      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Unapproved Decks, Pergolas and Carports: What Brisbane Sellers Must Address Before Listing
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Unapproved structures are one of the most common issues building inspectors flag in Brisbane. If your property has a deck, pergola, carport, or covered area built without council approval, here is what you need to do before you go to market.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Walk through enough Brisbane homes and you will encounter the same pattern: a beautifully built deck extending from the back of the house, a substantial pergola over the outdoor entertaining area, or a roofed carport along the side boundary. All of them built over the years by owners who wanted to improve their home. None of them with a building approval on record. This is one of the most common issues that comes up during building inspections and conveyancing checks in Brisbane, and sellers who know about it and deal with it early are in a much stronger position than those who discover it mid-campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What counts as an unapproved structure</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, most structures that are permanently attached to a property or that exceed certain size thresholds require a building approval from the relevant local authority. Decks above ground level, enclosed or roofed pergolas, carports and garages, covered outdoor entertaining areas, garden sheds beyond minor size limits, and secondary structures like pool sheds and cabanas are all typically covered by this requirement. The specific thresholds and triggers have changed over the years, but as a general rule: if it was built after the early 1970s and has a roof or is elevated, it almost certainly needed approval.</p>

      <p>The fact that it was built that way when you purchased the property does not protect you as a seller. If the approval was never obtained, the problem transfers with ownership unless it is addressed before or during your sale. Many Brisbane sellers are genuinely surprised to discover that the deck they bought the property for, or the garage they have used for twenty years, has no building approval on record.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why it matters when you sell</h2>
      <p>Brisbane City Council maintains online building records that are accessible to anyone. Buyers, their solicitors, and their lenders can pull the building approval history for your property within minutes of going to contract. A deck, pergola, or carport that does not appear in those records immediately raises questions.</p>

      <p>Building inspectors in Brisbane are also experienced at identifying structures that appear newer or inconsistent with the original construction of the home. A timber deck that was clearly added after the original build, or a carport with no matching permit, will be noted in a building inspection report. When a buyer reads that report and their solicitor confirms there is no corresponding approval on the council's records, the combination creates real negotiation pressure: requests for price reductions, demands for retrospective approval or removal before settlement, or in some cases termination of the contract where the special conditions allow for it.</p>

      <p>Buyers' lenders can also require unapproved structures to be resolved before they will advance funds. This is particularly common where the lender's valuer flags an unapproved structure in their report. If a buyer's finance is conditional and the lender requires resolution, the contract can quickly become complicated in ways that are difficult to manage from a seller's position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Your three options as a seller</h2>
      <p>When you identify an unapproved structure before listing, you have three practical paths forward.</p>

      <p>The first is to apply for retrospective building approval through Brisbane City Council by engaging a private building certifier. The certifier assesses whether the structure meets current building standards or whether it can be modified to comply. If the structure is soundly built and appropriately positioned for the site, retrospective approval is often achievable. Getting that approval before you list means you go to market with the issue resolved. The cost varies depending on the size and complexity of the structure, but for a standard timber deck or pergola the outlay is manageable relative to the negotiating leverage you give up by leaving the issue unresolved.</p>

      <p>The second option is to remove the structure before listing. This is the right call when a structure clearly does not meet current standards, when it is in poor condition, or when the cost of retrospective approval makes removal the more economical choice. Removing a structure that was adding limited value anyway and replacing it with a well-presented open outdoor space can sometimes improve a property's appeal rather than diminishing it.</p>

      <p>The third option is to disclose the unapproved structure in your contract and price accordingly. This is a transparent approach but it requires clear advice from your agent and solicitor about how to structure the disclosure and how buyers are likely to respond. In some markets and price brackets, buyers will accept an unapproved structure if it is honestly disclosed, is structurally sound, and is priced to reflect the risk they are taking on. In others, particularly in the prestige market and in transactions where the buyer's lender is closely involved, this approach creates more complications than it resolves.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the retrospective approval process works</h2>
      <p>Retrospective building approval in Brisbane begins with engaging a private building certifier, who acts independently of council to assess whether the structure complies with the Building Code of Australia and relevant Queensland regulations. The certifier inspects the structure, reviews how it was built, and determines whether it meets current standards as-is, whether modifications would bring it into compliance, or whether it cannot be made to comply in its current form.</p>

      <p>If the structure passes assessment, the certifier issues a building approval and the structure is registered in council records. This is the cleanest possible outcome for a sale. If the structure needs modifications, those need to be completed and signed off before the approval is issued. If the structure cannot be approved, removal is the only option.</p>

      <p>Engaging a certifier early, ideally several months before you intend to list, gives you the time to work through this process without campaign pressure. A certifier engaged the week before your listing date has the same information but you have far less flexibility in how you respond to what they find.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a buyer's solicitor will look for</h2>
      <p>When a buyer's solicitor does their due diligence on a Brisbane property, the council records search is standard. They are looking at what has been approved, what has been built, and whether those two things match. Any structure that appears on site but not in the approval records will be flagged for their client. This is not the solicitor being difficult: it is them doing exactly what they are paid to do. The seller's best response is to have dealt with the issue before it becomes something a solicitor needs to flag.</p>

      <p>In contracts where the buyer has a building and pest inspection condition, the building inspector's report and the conveyancing search results are often read side by side. An unapproved structure that appears in both creates compounding pressure: the inspector notes the structural concern and the solicitor confirms there is no approval. Sellers who have resolved the issue before those reports are produced are in a fundamentally different position.</p>

